     1	# AGENTS.md
     2	
     3	This file provides guidance to AI agents working with this repository.
     4	
     5	## What this repo is
     6	
     7	EDEN is a **protocol** for directed-code-evolution orchestration, not a
     8	single product. The repo contains three distinct kinds of artifact, each
     9	with different change discipline:
    10	
    11	| Layer | Path | Authoritative? | Change discipline |
    12	|---|---|---|---|
    13	| Protocol specification | [`spec/`](spec/) | Yes — the source of truth | RFC-style: versioned, normative (MUST/SHOULD/MAY), carefully reviewed |
    14	| Reference implementation | [`reference/`](reference/) | No — *one* valid impl | Normal code-review discipline |
    15	| Conformance suite | [`conformance/`](conformance/) | Normative for tests | Black-box; must be implementation-agnostic |
    16	
    17	Non-normative human docs live in [`docs/`](docs/).
    18	
    19	## Current phase
    20	
    21	**Phase 3 complete.** The `reference/packages/eden-contracts` package
    22	ships Pydantic v2 bindings for the six spec/v0 JSON Schemas, along with
    23	the first Python toolchain wiring (uv workspace, ruff, pyright, pytest)
    24	and four new CI jobs — `python-lint`, `python-typecheck`, `python-test`,
    25	and `schema-parity`. All six CI checks on `main` are green. See
    26	[`docs/roadmap.md`](docs/roadmap.md) for the full 13-phase plan. Phase 4
    27	is next: the event protocol, integrator chapter, and storage chapter —
    28	and the corresponding event schema.
    29	
    30	## Commands
    31	
    32	At Phase 3, markdown linting, JSON Schema validation, and the Python
    33	toolchain for the `eden-contracts` reference package are wired up.
    34	
    35	| Command | Purpose |
    36	|---|---|
    37	| `npx --yes markdownlint-cli2@0.14.0 "**/*.md" "#node_modules" "#.venv" "#docs/archive/**" "#docs/plans/review/**"` | Lint all tracked markdown (pinned to CI's version; matches CI exactly) |
    38	| `pipx run 'check-jsonschema==0.29.4' --check-metaschema spec/v0/schemas/*.schema.json` | Validate each schema file against the Draft 2020-12 meta-schema (version pinned to CI) |
    39	| `pipx run 'check-jsonschema==0.29.4' --schemafile spec/v0/schemas/experiment-config.schema.json tests/fixtures/experiment/.eden/config.yaml` | Validate the fixture experiment config against its schema |
    40	| `uv sync` | Install/refresh the workspace virtualenv (root + `reference/packages/eden-contracts`) |
    41	| `uv run ruff check .` | Lint Python (config in root `pyproject.toml`) |
    42	| `uv run pyright` | Type-check the reference Python packages |
    43	| `uv run pytest -q` | Run the reference-package test suite (includes schema ↔ model parity) |
    44	| `uv run pytest reference/packages/eden-contracts/tests/test_schema_parity.py` | Run only the schema ↔ Pydantic model parity check |
    45	
    46	### Commands that will exist in later phases
    47	
    48	These are listed for orientation; the tooling is not wired up yet.
    49	
    50	| Command | Lands in |
    51	|---|---|
    52	| `docker compose up` end-to-end | Phase 10 |
    53	
    54	## Contribution conventions
    55	
    56	### Spec edits
    57	
    58	+ Every cross-component contract (wire format, state machine, invariant)
    59	  is defined in `spec/` first, then implemented in `reference/`. When
    60	  they disagree, the spec wins and the impl gets a bug.
    61	+ Spec chapters use RFC 2119 language: MUST, SHOULD, MAY.
    62	+ Spec versions are frozen once stable (`spec/v0/` is a single lineage;
    63	  breaking changes go to `spec/v1/`).
    64	+ Schema changes must update the spec prose, the JSON Schema file, and
    65	  (from Phase 3 onward) the Pydantic bindings in lockstep. CI will
    66	  enforce schema ↔ model parity once both exist.
    67	
    68	### Reference implementation
    69	
    70	+ Normal code-review discipline.
    71	+ Normative behavior is tested against the conformance suite (once it
    72	  exists in Phase 11).
    73	+ The reference impl is explicitly not a monopoly on correctness. A
    74	  third-party implementation that passes conformance is equally valid.
    75	
    76	## Commit guidelines
    77	
    78	+ Short imperative subjects (e.g., "Add event protocol chapter",
    79	  "Pin task state machine").
    80	+ For pull requests, include: what the change is, which phase it
    81	  advances, and any spec ↔ impl implications.
    82	
    83	## Related docs
    84	
    85	+ [`docs/naming.md`](docs/naming.md) — what EDEN is, at the concept level.
    86	+ [`docs/roadmap.md`](docs/roadmap.md) — the 13-phase build-up plan with
    87	  unit-level decomposition.
    88	+ [`docs/plans/`](docs/plans/) — active implementation plans.
    89	+ [`docs/archive/`](docs/archive/) — historical reference docs.
    90	+ [`STYLE_GUIDE.md`](STYLE_GUIDE.md) — formatting and naming conventions.
    91	+ [`CONTRIBUTING.md`](CONTRIBUTING.md) — setup and PR workflow.
---
     1	# EDEN
     2	
     3	**E**ric's **D**irected **E**volution **N**exus — a protocol for
     4	orchestrating directed code evolution, with an open reference
     5	implementation and a conformance suite.
     6	
     7	EDEN is not a single system. It is a specification that defines the roles
     8	(planner, implementer, evaluator, integrator), the messages they exchange,
     9	and the invariants they must honor. Anyone can build a conforming planner,
    10	implementer, evaluator, or backing store in any language and interoperate
    11	with other conforming components.
    12	
    13	> **Intelligent evolution.**
    14	
    15	## What's in this repo
    16	
    17	| Directory | Purpose |
    18	|---|---|
    19	| [`spec/`](spec/) | Normative protocol specification. Versioned (`spec/v0/`, `spec/v1/`, …). The authoritative source. |
    20	| [`reference/`](reference/) | One complete implementation of the protocol. Labeled as a reference — *one* valid implementation, not *the* implementation. |
    21	| [`conformance/`](conformance/) | Black-box test suite any third-party component can run against itself to prove it conforms. |
    22	| [`docs/`](docs/) | Non-normative human documentation. Starts with [`docs/naming.md`](docs/naming.md) (what EDEN is) and [`docs/roadmap.md`](docs/roadmap.md) (how we build up to the full protocol). |
    23	
    24	## Status
    25	
    26	**Phase 3 complete.** The reference repository now ships its first
    27	Python package, `reference/packages/eden-contracts` — Pydantic v2
    28	bindings for all six spec/v0 JSON Schemas, with a discriminated-union
    29	task model, strict numeric parsing, URI and date-time format
    30	validation, and enforcement of the cross-field invariants the schemas
    31	express via `if/then/else` (task claim-presence, per-kind payloads,
    32	reserved metric names). A uv workspace wires ruff, pyright, and pytest
    33	at the repo root, and CI now runs six jobs — `docs-lint`,
    34	`schema-validity`, `python-lint`, `python-typecheck`, `python-test`,
    35	and `schema-parity`. The `schema-parity` job enforces that every
    36	fixture accepted by the models is also accepted by the JSON Schemas
    37	and vice versa, plus a round-trip check on `model_dump(exclude_none=
    38	True)`. There is still **no end-to-end runnable orchestration** —
    39	that starts landing in Phase 5. Phase 4 is next: event protocol,
    40	integrator, and storage specification. See
    41	[`docs/roadmap.md`](docs/roadmap.md) for the full Phase 0–13 plan.
    42	
    43	## Contributing
    44	
    45	See [`CONTRIBUTING.md`](CONTRIBUTING.md). Two paths:
    46	
    47	- **Spec contributions** follow RFC-style discipline: versioned, normative
    48	  language (RFC 2119 MUST/SHOULD/MAY), careful review.
    49	- **Reference-implementation contributions** follow standard code-review
    50	  workflow.
    51	
    52	## License
    53	
    54	[MIT](LICENSE).
---
     1	# Contributing to EDEN
     2	
     3	Thanks for your interest in EDEN.
     4	
     5	EDEN is a **protocol** for directed-code-evolution orchestration. This repo
     6	contains three kinds of artifact that call for different contribution
     7	discipline: the **specification** (`spec/`), the **reference
     8	implementation** (`reference/`), and the **conformance suite**
     9	(`conformance/`). Read the section that matches where your change lives.
    10	
    11	## Current phase
    12	
    13	**Phase 3 complete.** The spec/v0 core concepts, role contracts, task
    14	protocol, and six JSON Schemas are on the protected `main` alongside
    15	the Pydantic reference bindings in `reference/packages/eden-contracts`
    16	and a full Python toolchain (uv workspace + ruff + pyright + pytest).
    17	CI runs six checks — `docs-lint`, `schema-validity`, `python-lint`,
    18	`python-typecheck`, `python-test`, and `schema-parity`. See
    19	[`docs/roadmap.md`](docs/roadmap.md) for the remaining Phase 4–13 work.
    20	
    21	If you want to contribute, the most useful next areas are the Phase 4
    22	chapters (event protocol, integrator, storage) and any gaps you spot
    23	in the spec or the contracts-package bindings.
    24	
    25	## Contributing to the spec
    26	
    27	The spec is the authoritative source of protocol semantics. A change to
    28	the spec is a change to what "EDEN" means.
    29	
    30	### Spec conventions
    31	
    32	- **Versioning.** `spec/v0/` is a single lineage. Within a version,
    33	  changes should be additive or clarifying. Breaking changes go to a new
    34	  version (`spec/v1/`, …), never in-place.
    35	- **Normative language.** Use RFC 2119 keywords: **MUST**, **SHOULD**,
    36	  **MAY**. If prose doesn't use one, it's informative.
    37	- **Wire-format changes propagate.** A change to a JSON Schema file
    38	  under `spec/v*/schemas/` must be reflected in the Markdown chapter
    39	  and in the Pydantic bindings in `reference/packages/eden-contracts/`.
    40	  CI's `schema-parity` job enforces that models and schemas agree on
    41	  the accept/reject corpus and on round-trip emission.
    42	- **No technology choices in normative text.** The spec talks about
    43	  *semantics*, not mechanisms. "A conforming task store MUST provide
    44	  atomic claim with linearizable semantics" — yes. "Uses Postgres `SELECT
    45	  ... FOR UPDATE`" — no, that's reference-impl detail.
    46	
    47	### Process
    48	
    49	1. Open an issue describing the change and why. Spec changes benefit from
    50	   discussion before implementation.
    51	2. Draft the prose + schema change in a branch.
    52	3. Open a PR; expect careful review. Reviewers will check: RFC language,
    53	   cross-reference consistency, whether the change is additive or
    54	   breaking, and whether the change needs a conformance scenario.
    55	
    56	## Contributing to the reference implementation
    57	
    58	Standard code-review workflow applies.
    59	
    60	### Prerequisites
    61	
    62	Contributors touching the reference implementation need:
    63	
    64	- Python 3.12+
    65	- [uv](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/) (run `uv sync` at the repo root to
    66	  install the workspace virtualenv)
    67	- (Phase 9+) Node.js 20+ for the reference web UI
    68	- (Phase 10+) Docker for the Compose stack
    69	
    70	Spec-only contributors need only the Node-based markdown linter; see
    71	[`AGENTS.md`](AGENTS.md#commands) for the exact pinned commands
    72	(version-matched to CI to avoid works-locally / fails-in-CI drift).
    73	
    74	### Impl conventions
    75	
    76	- Normative behavior in the reference impl must match the spec. If the
    77	  impl is correct and the spec is wrong, the spec should change first.
    78	- Pass the conformance suite (Phase 11+).
    79	- Follow the [style guide](STYLE_GUIDE.md).
    80	
    81	## Contributing to the conformance suite
    82	
    83	The conformance suite lands in Phase 11 and is not yet implementable.
    84	Once it exists:
    85	
    86	- Scenarios must be **implementation-agnostic** — they drive an
    87	  implementation-under-test via its advertised protocol surface, not via
    88	  language-specific hooks.
    89	- A scenario must cite the spec paragraph it validates.
    90	
    91	## Questions
    92	
    93	Open an issue.

