**Findings**
- `Bug` [_common.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/reference/packages/eden-contracts/src/eden_contracts/_common.py:26), [conftest.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/reference/packages/eden-contracts/tests/conftest.py:53), [cases.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/reference/packages/eden-contracts/tests/cases.py:618): the round 1 URI fix is still only a “has a scheme” check, not real URI validation. `urlparse()` will happily accept malformed schemeful strings, and both the model and schema-side checker now share that weakness, so parity stays green while bad inputs slip through. I verified that `Proposal.artifacts_uri="http://exa mple.com/path"` and `Trial.artifacts_uri="http://exa mple.com/path"` both validate today. Fix: use an actual RFC-3986 validator in the string-preserving path, then add reject corpus cases for malformed schemeful URIs, not just “missing scheme”.

**Overall**
This is much tighter than round 0. The numeric-coercion gap is closed, explicit `null` handling now matches the schemas, impossible datetimes are rejected, the parity harness is stronger, and the status prose updates are accurate. Phase 3 scope and CI/workspace integration look good; I re-verified `uv sync --frozen`, `uv run pytest -q`, and the previously failing numeric/null/datetime cases.

I’d keep this at `Request Changes` for the remaining URI-fidelity bug. Other than that, I don’t see new regressions or meaningful scope creep in the round 1 update.
